ce:section.ce:para:
To comprehensively evaluate the applicability of the sensor in practical applications, this study employs fluorescence techniques to detect Difloxacin (DIF) in milk samples. After optimizing the conditions, different concentrations of DIF standard solutions are added to blank milk samples, and their fluorescence intensities are meticulously recorded. Based on the standard curve, the recovery rate and relative standard deviation (RSD) of the samples are calculated, as shown in Table 1
                        . The recovery rate ranges from 95.91 % to 101.87 %, and the RSD ranges from 0.88 % to 1.22 %. Comparing the actual sample analysis method with the HPLC method (Table 2
                        ), the advantages of b-CDs as sensors for the detection of difloxacin in milk can be demonstrated. These results adequately demonstrate the method's superiority in terms of accuracy and precision, confirming its practical application in detecting DIF in milk.
